    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "From FlashAttention-1 to FlashAttention-3"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FlashAttention has evolved through three major versions, each addressing the bottlenecks left by its predecessor. The core IO-aware tiling principle (introduced in FA1) remains unchanged \u2014 the improvements target parallelism, hardware utilisation, and new GPU capabilities:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "FlashAttention evolution: FA1 vs FA2 vs FA3"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FlashAttention-2: Improved Parallelism"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FA1's inner loop iterates over K/V tiles for a fixed Q tile. This limits the degree of parallelism to batch size \u00d7 heads \u2014 too small for modern GPU counts. FA2 restructures the loop so the outer dimension is Q tiles, enabling each thread-block to own a slice of the sequence independently:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# FA1-style: outer loop over KV tiles, inner over Q tiles\n# GPU utilisation bottleneck: only B*H thread-blocks\nfor q_tile in range(Tr):         # FA1: inner loop\n    m, l, O = init()\n    for kv_tile in range(Tc):   # FA1: outer loop \u2014 limits parallelism\n        m, l, O = update(m, l, O, kv_tile, q_tile)\n    write_output(O, q_tile)\n\n# FA2-style: outer loop over Q tiles \u2192 B*H*Tr thread-blocks\n# Each thread-block owns one Q tile completely\nfor q_tile in range(Tr):         # FA2: outer loop \u2014 high parallelism\n    m, l, O = init()\n    for kv_tile in range(Tc):\n        m, l, O = update(m, l, O, kv_tile, q_tile)\n    write_output(O / l, q_tile)  # normalise once per Q tile"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This restructuring has two benefits: the thread-block count scales as B \u00d7 H \u00d7 N/Br (proportional to sequence length), and forward and backward passes can share the same outer-loop structure, making the backward pass simpler to implement correctly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Causal Masking: Only Boundary Tiles Pay the Penalty"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For causal (autoregressive) attention, FA1 applied the mask to every KV tile, inserting conditional branches into every inner iteration. FA2 observes that the causal mask only affects the diagonal tiles where i \u2248 j. Tiles strictly above the diagonal can be skipped entirely (all zeros after masking), and tiles strictly below the diagonal are fully unmasked \u2014 only the boundary tiles need the conditional:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def fa2_causal_forward(Q, K, V, Br=64, Bc=64):\n    \"\"\"\n    Causal attention with boundary-tile optimisation.\n    - Above-diagonal tiles: skip (Q row < KV col \u2192 future tokens)\n    - Diagonal tiles: apply mask\n    - Below-diagonal tiles: full unmasked computation\n    \"\"\"\n    import torch\n    N, d = Q.shape\n    Tr = (N + Br - 1) // Br\n    Tc = (N + Bc - 1) // Bc\n    O = torch.zeros_like(Q)\n    L = torch.full((N,), float(\"-inf\"))   # log-sum-exp for backward\n    M = torch.full((N,), float(\"-inf\"))   # running max\n\n    for i in range(Tr):\n        q_start, q_end = i * Br, min((i + 1) * Br, N)\n        Qi = Q[q_start:q_end]\n        mi = torch.full((q_end - q_start,), float(\"-inf\"))\n        li = torch.zeros(q_end - q_start)\n        Oi = torch.zeros(q_end - q_start, d)\n\n        for j in range(Tc):\n            kv_start, kv_end = j * Bc, min((j + 1) * Bc, N)\n            if kv_start >= q_end:          # above diagonal: all future \u2192 skip\n                break\n            Kj = K[kv_start:kv_end]\n            Vj = V[kv_start:kv_end]\n\n            Sij = Qi @ Kj.T / (d ** 0.5)\n\n            if kv_end > q_start:           # boundary tile: apply mask\n                mask = torch.arange(q_start, q_end).unsqueeze(1) >=                        torch.arange(kv_start, kv_end).unsqueeze(0)\n                Sij = Sij.masked_fill(~mask, float(\"-inf\"))\n            # else: below diagonal \u2014 fully unmasked, no branch\n\n            m_new = torch.maximum(mi, Sij.max(dim=1).values)\n            P = torch.exp(Sij - m_new.unsqueeze(1))\n            alpha = torch.exp(mi - m_new)\n            li = alpha * li + P.sum(dim=1)\n            Oi = alpha.unsqueeze(1) * Oi + P @ Vj\n            mi = m_new\n\n        O[q_start:q_end] = Oi / li.unsqueeze(1)\n    return O"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "GQA and MQA Support in FA2"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Grouped Query Attention (GQA) and Multi-Query Attention (MQA) reduce KV-cache size by sharing key/value heads across query heads. FA2 supports GQA natively in its CUDA kernels without materialising replicated K/V tensors:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nfrom flash_attn import flash_attn_func\n\n# Standard MHA: H_q == H_kv\nB, H, N, d = 2, 32, 4096, 128\nq = torch.randn(B, N, H, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nk = torch.randn(B, N, H, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nv = torch.randn(B, N, H, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nout_mha = flash_attn_func(q, k, v, causal=True)\n\n# GQA: H_q groups of H_kv heads (e.g. H_q=32, H_kv=8 \u2192 4 query heads per KV head)\nH_kv = 8\nk_gqa = torch.randn(B, N, H_kv, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nv_gqa = torch.randn(B, N, H_kv, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\n# flash_attn_func accepts H_kv != H_q; internally handles head broadcasting\nout_gqa = flash_attn_func(q, k_gqa, v_gqa, causal=True)\n# out_gqa.shape == (B, N, H, d)  \u2190 full query-head output\n\n# MQA: H_kv = 1 (single KV head for all query heads)\nk_mqa = torch.randn(B, N, 1, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nv_mqa = torch.randn(B, N, 1, d, dtype=torch.float16, device=\"cuda\")\nout_mqa = flash_attn_func(q, k_mqa, v_mqa, causal=True)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "GQA support eliminates the need for explicit "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "torch.repeat_interleave"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " on K/V before attention \u2014 a pattern that both wastes VRAM and adds unnecessary HBM traffic:"
          }
        ]
      },
